column174: 'name': ""En Afrique le numérique en levier de l'entrepreneuriat pour les femmes""
column176: 'description': ""Il est passionnant de suivre l’engouement autour de entrepreneuriat en Afrique et particulièrement la synergie qui s’opère avec le numérique ces 10 dernières années.\nLes solutions qui visaient à développer des systèmes purement numériques ne sont plus... Le retour à une véritable analyse du contexte ou le manque de formation et d'encadrement sur les projets ont eu raison de beaucoup d'initiatives avec pour résultat concret une réorientation plus efficiente et profitable des services proposés. En marge les projets qui incluent le numérique
column177: porté par un nombre grandissant d'acteurs
column178: est devenu non plus un axe majeur mais un réel levier en synergie des thématiques du développement. Les femmes sont bien souvent les représentantes de ces thématiques dans les projets
column179: elles y développent donc logiquement un savoir-faire indispensable avec une légitimité plus que jamais d'actualité.\nDes femmes qui s'impliquent au cœur des dispositifs et qui savent
column180: que quels que soient l'échelle le produit sa réplicabilité ou ses bénéficiaires que ce qui rendra le projet viable
column181: c'est son rôle indispensable de service. Un service en adéquation avec le contexte et les spécificités du marché local. Une analyse précieuse mais hélas trop rarement mise en avant.""

'description': ""Accompagnement et mentor sur des porteurs de projets qui allient numérique et Afrique.

column178: 'name': 'Enquête sociologique sur la liste ""Francheville écologie""\u200b lors des élections municipales de 2014'
column180: nous avons suivi la liste indépendante ""Francheville écologie"" qui a obtenu 12
column181: 83% des suffrages au premier tour des élections. \n\nEn découvrant les positions politiques des groupes présents sur la scène locale
column182: nous avons remarqué le monopole à gauche exercé par l’équipe socialiste sortante et un pluralisme de trois groupes à droite qui s’étaient alliés afin de garantir la victoire. Les résultats de l’élection ont été remportées par la liste de droite “Francheville autrement” avec 53
column183: 89% des voix obtenues au second tour face à la liste fusionnée “Francheville au cœur / Francheville Ecologie”
column185: 79% des voix par le cumul des deux listes au premier tour. “Francheville écologie” était alloué de 12
column187: lui laissant ainsi le choix de s’allier ou de se présenter en triangulaires et risquant ainsi de faire échouer la gauche. Le sentiment de trahison exprimé par la liste socialiste face à la construction d’une liste écologiste a poussé les colistiers à se défendre et affirmer une réelle légitimité de leur projet. Constituer une liste avec des personnes possédant peu de capital politique a impliqué un investissement conséquent par ceux qui possédaient
column190: afin de rendre l’alternative écologiste crédible et professionnelle. \n\nNotre enquête s\'est ainsi attelé à identifier la mobilisation de capital politique et de ressources propres aux colistiers et plus particulièrement à la tête de liste
column191: afin de rendre la liste ""Francheville écologie"" légitime. Il s\'agissait alors d\'évaluer comment les grandes orientations écologistes sont reprises au niveau local et quelles compétences personnelles étaient valorisées lors de cette campagne municipale. '

column193: 'name': 'The Role of Rookie Female Directors in a Post‐Quota Period: Gender Inequalities within French Boards'
column194: 'publisher': 'Industrial Relations : A Journal of Economy and Society'
column195: 'description': 'The board‐level gender quota enacted in France has induced the massive arrival in corporate boards of a new population—namely
column196: women with no prior board experience. We examine the positions and the compensation of these “rookie female directors.” We show that
column197: conditional on their individual characteristics and firm effects
column198: rookie female directors have had a limited access to the key positions within boards and have suffered from a significant compensation gap. We interpret this evidence of positional segregation as resulting from gender stereotypes that have persisted in the process of rookie female directors’ integration within boards.'
column239: 'publisher': 'Handbook of the International Political Economy of the Corporation
column241: 'description': 'This chapter provides an overview of the literature on corporate governance and corporate accountability
column242: focusing on listed companies. It first surveys the normative debate on corporate responsibility
column243: opposing two antagonistic models: the shareholder primacy model and the corporate social responsibility model. It then relates this (normative) diversity to the empirical diversity in corporate governance systems. The following sections narrow the scope of the analysis
column244: to discuss in more details two crucial governance mechanisms and their effects on various firm outcomes: the distribution of stock ownership
column245: and the composition and functioning of the board of directors.'
column285: 'name': 'How to foster responsible corporate governance? Voluntary versus legislative approaches'
column291: is regulated in most jurisdictions by voluntary and legislative instruments
column292: as a way to foster good practices
column293: responsible behavior and firm performance. Understanding the relative costs and benefits of the two approaches is therefore an important question. This chapter proposes a first step in this direction
column294: by investigating and comparing how French listed companies (SBF 120) comply with the AFEP-MEDEF code of corporate governance regarding independence on one side and the mandatory board gender quota on the other. The chapter reviews the literature on board composition and firm performance
column295: and related soft and hard regulations. It reports that independent and female directors have specific individual characteristics that may influence the overall impact of the regulation (soft or hard). Furthermore
column296: it shows that while independent directors have become key players inside the boardroom through committee assignment
column297: women still face an indirect inner glass ceiling that may jeopardize the efficiency of the quota.'
column337: 'name': 'Le conseil d’administration: enjeux de gouvernance et de responsabilité'
column339: 'description': ""Cet article se propose de faire le point sur les recherches en gouvernance d'entreprises. Les principales thématiques sont illustrées à partir de chiffres sur les conseils d’administration des sociétés du SBF120 pour la période 2007-2015. Dans une première partie
column340: on s’intéresse au fonctionnement du conseil : il s’agit d’une question centrale mais
column341: du fait d’un manque d’informations ou de données disponibles
column342: encore peu couverte par la recherche. La deuxième partie traite de la composition du conseil ; la littérature académique y est beaucoup plus fournie. On identifie un déplacement des préoccupations
column343: de la question de l’indépendance à celle de la diversité. La dernière partie s’attache plus spécifiquement à la diversité de genre au sein des conseils
column344: compte tenu de l’importance qu’a prise cette question depuis quelques années. Au terme de cette revue
column345: il apparaît que le conseil est véritablement l’organe de pouvoir central des grandes sociétés de capitaux
column346: dont l’étude éclaire aussi bien les enjeux de performance
column347: de gouvernance et de responsabilité des entreprises.""
column386: 'name': 'Objectifs de Développement durable et entreprise : enjeux et opportunité'
column390: sont  incitées   à   inscrire   leur   stratégie   et   leur   gouvernance dans le cadre des Objectifs de Développement Durable
column391: notamment en y projetant leur cœur de métier
column392: en y repensant leur modèle d’affaires et en y développant leur Responsabilité Sociétale. Cette publication présente les éléments principaux d'analyse.""
column468: 'name': ""Quota législatif vs. code de gouvernance : quels effets sur la parité Femmes/Hommes dans les conseils d'administration ? Une étude sur données britaniques et françaises""
column469: 'publisher': 'GIP Mission de recherche Droit et Justice'
column470: 'description': 'L’objectif de ce chapitre est d’étudier l’effectivité comparée de la hard law (loi) et de la soft law (code). Notre hypothèse est que des véhicules (supports
column473: produits au terme de processus de production juridique différents et dotés de modes d’application et de mise en oeuvre différents
column476: des effets eux – mêmes différents. Notre question est donc la suivante : la même disposition de gouvernance produit-elle des effets différents
column477: selon qu’elle soit portée par du droit légiféré (hard law) ou un code (soft law) ?\nPrécisément
column478: nous nous intéressons aux effets comparés d’une même disposition juridique
column479: destinée à promouvoir la parité entre femmes et hommes dans les conseils d’administration
column480: selon que cette disposition soit portée par un code de gouvernance d’entreprise ou par une loi (sous la forme d’un quota législatif). En d’autres termes
column481: nous étudions les effets d’un « choc régulatoire » (l’introduction
column483: d’une disposition similaire concernant la parité femmes / hommes par un code et un texte de loi respectivement
column484: en Grande-Bretagne et en France) sur la composition des conseils d’administration des entreprises des deux pays concernés. Notre objectif est de déterminer si les résultats observés aujourd’hui en termes de mixité genrée des conseils d’administration dans les deux pays
column486: peuvent s’expliquer par le choix du code ou de la loi (ou le quota législatif) pour promouvoir l’égalité femmes / hommes dans les conseils d’administration. Nous vérifions évidemment que les différences de performance actuelles des entreprises britanniques et françaises en matière d’égalité femmes / hommes dans les conseils ne sont pas imputables à d’autres facteurs que le choix du code vs. le quota législatif pour atteindre l’équilibre genré des conseils.'
column528: 'name': ""Gouvernance et Performances d'entreprise : quelle équation de durabilité?""
column530: 'description': ""Cette article est un résumé des travaux de thèse sur la gouvernance d'entreprise et la responsabilité sociétale au travers du prisme des conseils d'administration. Cette thèse s'intéresse à la composition des conseils d'administration et à l'efficacité de celui-ci à réaliser ses missions sous l'angle des régulations souples et législatives en France.""
column569: 'name': 'Mooc : un outil pour la transition écologique ?'
column571: 'description': ""Les Massive Open Online Courses sont des nouveaux formats d'apprentissage en ligne accessible librement. Cette publication met en évidence les usages possibles des MOOC dans les apprentissages en faveur de la transition écologique et solidaire.""
column636: 'name': 'Independent directors: less informed but better selected than affiliated directors?'
column638: 'description': 'This paper examines the relationships between independence
column639: director unobservable ability and firm performance. We develop an original empirical strategy based on the AKM model to estimate separately director fixed effects (as a measure of individual ability) and firm fixed effects. We show that board independence has an ambiguous impact on corporate performance because of two opposing forces: one related to the director nomination process
column640: the other one related to board functioning. On one hand
column641: we report that independence is positively correlated with individual fixed effects
column642: an evidence consistent with a nomination process of independent directors based on individual ability. On the other hand
column646: is negatively correlated with firm performance suggesting that independent board members experience an informational deficit (as compared to affiliated directors).'
column688: 'name': 'Board independence and operating performance: analysis on (French) company and individual data'
column690: 'description': 'This article studies the relationship between board independence and firm operating performance in French listed companies. We take advantage of an original database
column691: with a time-series dimension that can be used to mitigate heterogeneity and dynamic endogeneity issues. In addition
column692: this database can be disaggregated at the individual (director) level. This design enables us to introduce firm fixed effects and individual fixed effects in firm performance equations
column693: thereby controlling for heterogeneity at the firm and individual levels. Our main result is to document a significant negative relationship between independence and accounting performance. This result suggests that
column695: the costs of independence (i.e. the informational gap supported by independent directors compared to insiders and affiliated directors) outweigh the benefits of independence (i.e. the reduction in agency costs).'

column639: smartphones are transforming the way consumers shop. To cope with\nthe skyrocketing of e-commerce and the showrooming effect
column640:
retailers have
developed new marketing techniques to bridge the gap between the online and the
physical world. Although an increasing number of retailers are implementing
mobile marketing strategies based on beacons
column641: research on m-business suggests that\npotential consumers may be reluctant to adopt new mobile services. Thus
column642: there is\na need to better understand the consumer perception of Bluetooth-marketing. To do\nso
column643: we developed a new research model based on the perceived value and attitude
column644: \ntaking into account consumer’s trust and past experience. Data was collected from\n269 respondents
column645:
among French and Chinese consumers. The results strongly
support the proposed model in predicting consumer attitude toward Bluetooth
marketing. The present study highlights also the differences between the two
countries and makes several implications for retailers. The results indicate that trust
toward the service provider and consumer’s past experience
column646:
play a major role on
the perceived value of Bluetooth mobile marketing. The study also finds that the
perceived utilitarian value is the most important factor influencing the consumer
attitude toward Bluetooth marketing
column648: social and\nthe perceived risk. When comparing the two countries
column649: the utilitarian value and the\nperceived risk
column650: play a stronger role on the attitude among French than among\nChinese consumers. On the other side
column651: the perceived social value plays a stronger\nrole on the attitude among Chinese than among French consumers.'

column14: 'description': ""Entreprise pionnière et référente de la Civic Tech
column15:
Cap Collectif s’est donnée pour mission d’accompagner les décideurs qui souhaitent faire évoluer leur mode de décision vers plus de transparence et d’inclusion. 

Nous pensons que des processus participatifs sont susceptibles de :
- Améliorer l'efficacité des décisions prises.
- Renforcer la confiance.
- Renforcer l’adhésion à un projet.
- Développer l’envie d’agir sur un territoire ou au sein d'une organisation.

Dans le cadre de mes missions :
- J'anime des réseaux d'utilisateurs de notre solution.
- J'accompagne nos organisations partenaires dans leur utilisation de la plateforme au service de leurs projets.
- Je traite les demandes commerciales de nos clients et gère les aspects contractuels.

Chiffres clés :
- 400 organisations utilisatrices de notre logiciel dont +250 collectivités territoriales
- 1500 projets participatifs""

I worked in the Health Lab on the Open Chronic challenge
column2: which aims to improve chronic disease management using the french administrative health care database (SNDS).

column1: The SNDS is one of the largest health database worldwide. Its is highly complex and the necessary knowledge to work with it is scattered across multiple organizations. I worked to improve this state of affairs
column2: and make this knowledge flow openly.

column1: With the help of Health Data Hub team
column2: I set up a collaboration between users of SNDS

column6: 'description': 'La production et la consommation de biens et de services destinée à la satisfaction de nos besoins primaires se rationalisent (économie productive). column7: mais elles ont des caractéristiques opposées. Ce livre propose des pistes pour adapter nos outils de gouvernance et même en créer.'

column207: 'name': 'The spatial and enery impact of data centers'
column209: 'description': 'The spatial and energy impact of data centers is becoming more and more impacting for territories
column210: given the unprecedented and massive growth of data creation and exchanges
column211: leading to large storage needs. Data centers are very diverse in size
column213: stakeholders and sitings. This makes the understanding of their dynamics and spatial effects complex.\nThis report aims at describing the data center landscape in France and in three locations in the United States
column214: each being representative of different spatial and energy situations (rural
column216: urban). They are potentially disruptive of local energy systems
column217: and their accumulation in urban areas as their spreading in rural ones are a concern for urban and regional planning. Data centers are thoroughly analyzed here to better apprehend how new digital territories emerge
column218: how energy solidarities can be built and new governances implemented.\nThere is a specific focus on alternative digital infrastructures that have been developing
column220: South America and in the less connected territories of Europe and the United States. Dedicated to both Internet access and
column224: peer-to-peer response whose environmental impact seems ultimately more limited than the centralized and large-scale infrastructures
column225: because they are calibrated closer to the users’ needs. They also appear more resilient to climate events and computing attacks because less technically centralized and less spatially concentrated.\nThey are therefore an option to consider and support
column227: to reduce the spatial and energy impacts of data centers. The report presents prospective visions of three possible digital worlds
column228: based on global trends and emerging signals.'

column165: 'name': 'What if data protection regulators embraced foresight and speculative design ?'
column167: 'description': ""Due to rapid technological advancements and the growing “datafication” of\nour societies
column168: individuals’ privacy constitutes an increasingly explored speculative\nspace for regulators
column171: designers and artists. This article\nreports two experiences at a national and an international data protection authority\n(i.e.
column172: the Commission Nationale de l'Informatique et des Libertés - CNIL - and the\nEuropean Data Protection Supervisor - EDPS - respectively)
column173: where foresight methods\nand speculative design are employed in policy-making with the goal of anticipating\ntechnological trends
column174: their implications for society and their impact on regulations
column175: as\nwell as the effects of existing and upcoming laws on emerging technologies. Such\ninitiatives can enhance strategic proactive abilities
column176: raise public awareness of privacy\nissues and engender a participatory approach to the design of policies. They can also\ninspire the research
column177: education and practice of legal design.\n\nwith : Arianna Rossi

column363: depuis l’emplacement des packs d’eau à l’extrémité du magasin aux friandises disposées sur la caisse. column246: 'name': '""La Phénoménologie de Maurice Merleau-Ponty peut-elle servir de source d\'inspiration à l\'esthéticien industriel ?""\u200b'
column249: 'description': '""Can Maurice Merleau-Ponty\'s Phenomenology serve as an inspiration for the industrial designer ?""\u200b\n\nWhile methodically studying ""Phenomenology of Perception""\u200b by French mid 20th century philosopher Maurice Merleau-Ponty
column250: I did my utmost to prove that
column251: not only his philosophy and industrial design were born around the same time
column252: but they were also based on the same considerations. \nHis vision of human life is constructed on the concepts of perception
column253: surrounding natural world and perceiving body
column254: forming human behavior. This human condition is therefor undetermined but one can transcend this condition by making sense in what surrounds one. His conception of the object is what makes this philosophy interesting for the industrial designer. Merleau-Ponty considers that we perceive each ""human object""\u200b function
column255: as we ""experiment""\u200b the object with our body ; moreover each ""human object""\u200b is above all a ""natural object""\u200b
column256: so it can - and must - tend toward nature\'s harmony where everything expresses its inherent meaning. I link those concepts to the first industrial designers\'\u200b theories : Raymond Loewy in ""Never leave well enough alone""\u200b (1951) and Henry Dreyfuss in ""Designing for people""\u200b (1955). I also question the origin of this historical renewed appreciation of the human body.\nThis philosophical approach to industrial design is finally supposed to put some sense back to our material life
column258: within today\'s context of economic crisis
column260: and constant reflection on moral or identity. When industrial design makes our everyday life better
column261: makes us meet our fellow man through the object
column263: doesn\'t it tie in with philosophy on one of its main reason : the pursuit of happiness?'

column171: 'description': 'The Political Economy of Government Auditing addresses the elusive quest for greater transparency and accountability in the management of public finances in emerging economies; and
column173: it examines the contribution of autonomous audit agencies to the fight against corruption and waste.\n\n""This book is an important contribution to our understanding of how corruption can be prevented by strengthening those institutions tasked with scrutinizing government and overseeing public finances. It provides useful lessons to reformers in Latin America in their efforts to promote integrity in the use of public resources. These lessons of experience are also relevant for African countries pursuing the same objectives. "" Donald Kaberuka
column174: President of the African Development Bank and former Minister of Finance of Rwanda\n\n""Controlling corruption represents a fundamental challenge for all societies in their quest to improve the lives of the most vulnerable. Carlos Santiso eloquently demonstrates the importance of strengthening the institutions of integrity to combat corruption and
column176: enhance transparency and accountability in public finances. His analysis of the role of audit agencies will undoubtedly help reformers around the world in the fight against corruption and hopefully inspire others to further enhance our knowledge of these overlooked oversight institutions."" - Dr. Peter Eigen
column177: Founder of Transparency International\n\n""The book stresses in various places that
column179: the effectiveness of audit agencies does not depend only on organizational factors but also
column181: on the influence of political factors. For this reason these institutions cannot be copied from other countries and cannot be created over night. They must be created over a period of time and reflect the political reality of the countries. Dr. Santiso’s book is of particularly great value in this context."" - Vito Tanzi

column200: 'description': 'Behavioral sciences help refine our understanding of human decision-making. Their insights are immensely relevant for policy-making
column201: since public intervention works much better when it targets real people rather than imaginary beings assumed to be perfectly rational. Increasingly
column202: governments around the world are keen to rely on those insights for reshaping public interventions in a wide range of policy areas
column206: and data protection. When policy-making meets behavioral sciences
column207: effective and low-cost regulations can emerge in the form of default rules
column209: and simplification requirements. While behaviorally-informed intervention has a huge potential for policymaking
column210: it also attracts legitimacy and practicability concerns. This book takes a European perspective on those issues and explores the legal implications of the emergent phenomenon of behavioral regulation by focusing on the challenges and opportunities it may offer to EU policy-making and beyond. It will be a fascinating read for academics and practitioners working in the field of European law and consumer law
column211: as well as for policymakers. (Series: Modern Studies in European Law) [Subject: EU Law

column290: 'name': 'Nudging legally: On the Checks and Balances of Behavioural Regulation'
column292: 'description': 'As behavioral sciences are unearthing the complex cognitive framework in which people make decisions
column293: policymakers seem increasingly ready to design behaviorally informed regulations to induce behavior change in the interests of the individual and society. After discussing what behavioral sciences have to offer to administrative law
column294: this article explores the extent to which administrative law may accommodate their findings into the regulatory process. After presenting the main regulatory tools capable of operationalizing behavioral insights
column295: it builds a case for integrating them into public policymaking. In particular
column296: it identifies the need to develop a legal framework capable of ensuring that behavioral considerations may inform the regulatory process while at the same time guaranteeing citizens’ constitutional rights and freedoms vis-à-vis the regulatory state.'

column204: 'description': 'There is little political acknowledgment with regards to the impelling role nationally significant squares can have in revolutions. Inspired by David Siddhartha Patel’s original “Tahrir square model”
column205: our study aims to expand upon his work and test
column206: on a more global scale than his original Middle Eastern scope
column207: the role that geopolitically-important squares can play in spurring revolutionary fervor and subsequently
column208: instigating a revolution. Whilst in our study we found that important squares proved to have no significant effect in influencing revolutions
column209: there are a number of unaccounted for confounders which we were unable to include within our project. Due to this
column210: we believe that a more extensive research on the link between the two variables could eventually suggest a complex relationship.'
column211: 'title': '‘What effect does the presence of a nationally significant square have in influencing a revolution?’'}
